Introduction¶

  • This data set has been taken from 1984 United States Congressional Voting database and it includes votes for each of the U.S. House of Representatives Congressmen on the 16 key votes identified by the CQA(Congressional Quarterly Almanac).
  • The CQA lists nine different types of votes: voted for, paired for, and announced for (these three simplified to yea), voted against, paired against, and announced against (these three simplified to say), voted present, voted present to avoid conflict of interest, and did not vote or otherwise make a position known (these three simplified to an unknown disposition).

Data Source¶

  • Congressional Quarterly Almanac, 98th Congress, 2nd session 1984, https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Congressional+Voting+Records
  • It has 435 obervation. We are considering full dataset for further study. We will divide dataset with 75% as training and 25% as test dataset. Both dataset contains 16 descriptive features and 1 target feature (class name).

Objective¶

  • Using various classification techniques and associated hyperparameter tuning, we will try to predict class name (Party name), using various all features or selected features group from the dataset and identify most suitable technique.

Features¶

Target feature:¶

Our target feature is : Class Name, which is categorical feature, party name

  1. Class Name: 2 (democrat, republican)

Descriptive features:¶

  1. handicapped-infants: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  2. water-project-cost-sharing: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  3. adoption-of-the-budget-resolution: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  4. physician-fee-freeze: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  5. el-salvador-aid: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  6. religious-groups-in-schools: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  7. anti-satellite-test-ban: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  8. aid-to-nicaraguan-contras: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  9. mx-missile: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  10. immigration: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  11. synfuels-corporation-cutback: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  12. education-spending: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  13. superfund-right-to-sue: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  14. crime: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  15. duty-free-exports: 2 , binary values(Y/N)
  16. export-administration-act-south-africa: 2 , binary values(Y/N)

def colorDictionary(labels):
    dim_colors = cmap(np.linspace(0., 1., len(labels)))
    dim_colordict={}
    for l,c in zip(labels,dim_colors):
        # print l,c

Handling missing value:¶

  • Dataset feature contains missing values(NAN) and further step handles the same by replacing with median or mode based on datatype of each features.
In [9]:
# replace nan/? with mode and median
from statistics import mode
for i in df_col:
    # print(i)
    # Check for numerical features
    if df[i].dtypes in numerical_type:
        print("{0} median is {1}".format(i, df[i].median()))
        df[i] =df[i].replace(na_values,df[i].median())
    # Check for other object features
    elif df[i].dtypes == object:
        print("{0} mode is {1}".format(i, mode(df[i])))
        df[i] =df[i].replace(na_values,mode(df[i]))

Predictive Modelling:¶

- In this part we are going to apply 4 predictive modeling algorithms for (binary) classification.
- We are going to implement following algorithms:

    1) KNN(k-nearest neighbors) Algorithm
    2) Naive Bays Algorithm
    3) Decision Tree Algorithm
    4) Support Vector Classification Algorithm

- Here, we will be using classification algorithms rather than regression algorithms as it suits our dataset and setting categorical variable as target variable.
- We will split our dataset; 75% for training and 25% for testing randomly.
- Hypermeter Tuning; We will use different parameters like:

      (i) n_neighbors, p_value for KNN algorithm.
     (ii) 3 different models (Gaussian, Bernaulli and Complement) for Naive Bays Algorithm.
    (iii) max_depth, min_samples_split, min_samples_leaf and max_features for Decision Tree Algorithm.
     (iv) kernal, c_value and gamma for Support Vector Classifier. 

 - We further performed paired t-test with best tuned hyperparameter accuracy with other algorithms.

Model Evaluation Strategy:¶

   - We will use AUC Score for model evaluation for each iteration of tuned parameter.

KNN Implementation¶

- KNN algorithm is supervised machine learning algorithm based on distance from proximity.
- It is one of the most common yet powerful algorithm.

KNN Hyperparameter Tuning¶

1. No. of Neighbor
2. P-value (distance metric)

Hyperparameter(1) Tuning - No. of Neighbors¶

In [29]:
neighbors = list(range(1,30))
train_results = []
test_results = []
for n in neighbors:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n)
    knn.fit(x_train, y_train)
    train_pred = knn.predict(x_train)
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, train_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    train_results.append(roc_auc)
    y_pred = knn.predict(x_test)
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    test_results.append(roc_auc)

Hyperparameter(2) P-Value in Minkowski Distance¶

     p=2 -> Equivalent Euclidian Distance
     p=3,4,5 -> Arbitary p-value in Minkowski Distance

Decision Tree Classifier Hyperparameter Tuning¶

1. max_depth        
2. min_samples_split        
3. min_samples_leaf       
4. max_features

Hyperparameter(1) Tuning - Max Depth¶

   -> This indicates the depth of the tree.
   -> Deeper the tree, more it captures information about the data. 
   -> Varing depth from 1 to 32 and plot the training and test auc scores.
In [53]:
max_depths = np.linspace(1, 32, 32, endpoint=True)
train_results = []
test_results = []
for max_depth in max_depths:
    dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=max_depth)
    dt.fit(x_train, y_train)
    train_pred = dt.predict(x_train)
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, train_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    # Add auc score to previous train results
    train_results.append(roc_auc)
    y_pred = dt.predict(x_test)
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    # Add auc score to previous test results
    test_results.append(roc_auc)

dt_scores =[]
dt_scores.append(max(test_results))
index = test_results.index(max(test_results))
optimal_dt_depth = int(max_depths[index])
optimal_auc_dt_depth = max(test_results)
best_results_dt = test_results

Hyperparameter(2) Tuning - min_samples_split¶

   -> It represents the minimum number of samples required to split an internal node. 
   -> By increasing this parameter, the tree becomes more constrained as it has to consider more samples at each node. 
   -> Varing the parameter from 10% to 100% of the samples.
In [56]:

    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds =    roc_curve(y_train, train_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    train_results.append(roc_auc)
    y_pred = dt.predict(x_test)
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)

dt_scores.append(max(test_results))

Hyperparameter(2) Tuning - Gamma¶

-> Defines how much influence a single training example has.
In [75]:
scoresHigh = []
scoresLow = []
gamma_high = range(1,10)
gamma_low =[]

for gamma in gamma_high:
    svc = SVC(gamma=gamma)
    svc.fit(x_train, y_train)
    y_pred = svc.predict(x_test)
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
    svc_roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    svc_acc_per = round(svc_roc_auc*100, 3)
    scoresHigh.append(svc_acc_per)

for gamma in gamma_high:
    svc = SVC(gamma = gamma/100)
    gamma_low.append(gamma/100)
    svc.fit(x_train, y_train)
    y_pred = svc.predict(x_test)
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
    svc_roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    svc_acc_per = round(svc_roc_auc*100, 3)
    scoresLow.append(svc_acc_per)

r3= stats.ttest_rel(best_results_knn, best_results_svc)
print(r3)
r4= stats.ttest_rel(best_results_knn, best_results_nb)
print(r4)

Ttest_relResult(statistic=-1.803562203498009, pvalue=0.08718108334442755)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-7.64074719022136, pvalue=3.293475405229231e-07)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-16.806947103919256, pvalue=7.326537210185652e-13)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=0.3904745589842121, pvalue=0.7005290585289313)
  • A p-value smaller than 0.05 indicates a statistically significant difference. Looking at these results, we conclude that at a 95% significance level, SVC is statistically the best model in this competition (in terms of AUC) when compared on the test data.

Overall Classification Report¶

-Though we used AUC to optimize the algorithm hyperparameters, we shall consider the following metrics to evaluate models based on the test set:

-Accuracy
-Precision
-Recall
-F1 Score (the harmonic average of precision and recall)
-Confusion Matrix

-These metrics can be computed using classification_report from sklearn.metrics. The classification reports are shown below.

Limitations and Proposed Solutions¶

  • Our modeling strategy has a few flaws and limitations.

    (1) We could consider a more in-depth analysis about the feature selection while we did not performed feature selection in this process of classification & our choices for the hyperparameter spaces.

    (2) We considered the data is normally distrubuted for the purpose of classification.

    (3) We prefered changing the model for Naive Bays algorithm rather than tuning var_smoothing parameter.

    (4) We only worked with a small dataset of <500 rows, for both for training and testing.

    (5) While spliting we considered using random_sample = 0 in order to get same training and testing subsets with each iteration.

Summary¶

  • The SVC model with 13 as C-Value produces the highest AUC score on the training data. In addition, when evaluated on the test data using AUC Score, the SVC again outperforms Decision Tree, Naive Bayes and k-Nearest Neighbor models with respect to AUC. We utilized full set of features however we can select features using RFI.
  • Overall we can conclude that we sucessfully completed the objective by performing implementation of algorithms and performing various tuning iterations.
